sidebar.tutorialSidebar.category.Spring.message: Si alguna vez has intentado hornear un pastel desde cero, sabes que implica medir la harina, romper huevos y mezclar los ingredientes, todo antes de siquiera encender el horno. El desarrollo tradicional en Java puede resultar igual de tedioso. Descubre Spring Boot, la premezcla del mundo de la programación. Analicemos qué es y por qué a los desarrolladores les encanta.

sidebar.tutorialSidebar.category.Let’s C.message: Starting a Spring Boot project is like ordering a pizza—you pick your toppings (dependencies), crust (settings), and let the oven (Spring Initializr) handle the rest. No coding required yet! Here’s how to spin up a project in seconds.

sidebar.tutorialSidebar.category.Contrac.description: The label for category Contract-Driven Development in sidebar tutorialSidebar

sidebar.tutorialSidebar.category.Contrac.message: Usually when developing, we make our endpoint first, then we write documentation in an OpenAPI Specification. The problem appears later, when somebody else modifies the endpoint and now the documentation doesn’t reflect it. This can go unnoticed. Worse than no documentation, is wrong documentation. What if we wrote documentation first, and the code is generated from it? Let me introduce you to Contract-Driven Development.

sidebar.tutorialSidebar.category.Integra.message: In modern backend development, services often need to communicate with external web services using HTTP. Whether your service needs to integrate with third-party platforms, microservices, or legacy systems, the web client becomes a critical component of your application’s architecture.

sidebar.tutorialSidebar.category.Unit Te.message: Unit testing is the practice of testing individual pieces (units) of your code in isolation to verify they work correctly. Think of it like checking each ingredient before cooking a meal, rather than just tasting the final dish and trying to figure out what went wrong.

Few people are going to tell you this, but reality is working in Big Tech is bad. Let’s dissect common challenges, systemic issues and work mentalities.
